You will need to pivot the data into longer form, using the pivot_longer function.

You should know how to do the rest from your experience with past assignments.

fertility <-
  fertility_raw %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = -country, # everything but country,
               # what is the name of the new variable we are changing the
               # column of names to?
               names_to = "year_collected",
               # What is the name of the column we are changing the values to?
               values_to = "babies_per_woman") %>%
  #extract out the year information
  mutate(year = parse_number(year_collected)) %>%
  # filter so we only look at years above 1950
  filter( year > 1950) %>%
  # center year around 1950
  na.omit %>%
  mutate(year1950 = year - 1950)

plot the fertility data for each year

ggplot(fertility, 
       aes(x = year, 
           y = babies_per_woman, 
           group = country)) +
  geom_line(alpha=0.1)

Explore model fit for Australia

ggplot(data = oz_aug, 
       aes(x = year, 
           y = .fitted)) + 
  geom_line(colour = "blue") + 
  geom_point(aes(x = year,
                 y = babies_per_woman))

In Australia, for a unit inctrease in year, the ferility has decreased by -0.02883 on average 74.91% variance is explanined by this model.

How has fertility increased every year / decade in Australia?

for a unit inctrease in year, the ferility has decreased by -0.02883 on average. The increase prior to 1960, isnt explained by this model.

How well does the model fit?

ggplot(data = oz_aug, 
             aes(x = year, 
                 y = .std.resid)) + 
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0,
             colour = "white", 
             size = 2) +
  geom_line()

74.91% variance is explanined by this model. A lot of unexplained variance. Fertility has decreased 0.28 years every decade, on average.
